Root-level files coordinate the workspace. They are not the place to duplicate detailed submodule internals unless the information is genuinely cross-cutting.

## Root file role

Keep root-level files focused on:

- workspace-wide developer workflows
- aggregate commands
- environment coordination
- milestone/task navigation
- cross-submodule integration points

Prefer referencing submodule-local detail instead of re-documenting it extensively in the root.

## Stable interfaces

Treat root entrypoints as stable interfaces unless the task explicitly changes them.

This includes, when relevant:

- `make` targets exposed by the root `Makefile` (including `test` and `test-guards`)
- `./scripts/sv0 ...` subcommands (`test` runs the full harness; `test-guards` runs only the Python guard trio: block comments, sv0doc baseline paths, task `*.Rmd` YAML)
- task-document entrypoints in `task/`

If one of these interfaces changes, update all affected root docs and validation steps consistently.

## Command consistency

When editing command docs or orchestration:

- keep command names, intent, and expected sequencing aligned
- avoid introducing undocumented command aliases casually
- prefer one canonical root command per workflow where possible

## Task index discipline

Treat top-level task documents as navigation and orchestration artifacts.

They should remain easy to scan and should continue to point a developer or agent toward the correct owning document or submodule.

## Avoid

Do not let root docs become a second spec.
Do not let root scripts become an undocumented compatibility layer.
Do not move submodule-local behavior into the root without a clear cross-cutting reason.
